The United States Customs and Border Protection officers have impounded 14,806 pairs of fake Nike shoes that, if genuine, would’ve been worth a total of more than $2 million (N721 million). <img class="alignnone wp-image-1269095" src="https://i1.wp.com/cdn.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/Nike.jpg?resize=359%2C202&#038;ssl=1" alt="US Customs impounds more than 14,000 fake Nike shoes from China" width="359" height="202" srcset="https://i1.wp.com/cdn.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/Nike.jpg?resize=300%2C169&amp;ssl=1 300w, https://i1.wp.com/cdn.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/Nike.jpg?resize=768%2C431&amp;ssl=1 768w, https://i1.wp.com/cdn.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/Nike.jpg?resize=1024%2C575&amp;ssl=1 1024w, https://i1.wp.com/cdn.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/Nike.jpg?resize=58%2C33&amp;ssl=1 58w, https://i1.wp.com/cdn.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/Nike.jpg?resize=260%2C146&amp;ssl=1 260w, https://i1.wp.com/cdn.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/Nike.jpg?resize=200%2C112&amp;ssl=1 200w, https://i1.wp.com/cdn.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/Nike.jpg?resize=560%2C315&amp;ssl=1 560w, https://i1.wp.com/cdn.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/Nike.jpg?w=1287&amp;ssl=1 1287w" sizes="(max-width: 359px) 100vw, 359px" data-recalc-dims="1" /> The shoes arrived from China at the Los Angeles/Long Beach Seaport in containers marked as “napkins.” What was inside weren’t napkins at all, but instead shoes meant to look like pairs of special-edition Nikes. Agents found the coveted classic styles of Air Jordan 1 Off-White; Air Jordan 12; Air Jordan 1 in blue, black, red and white; Air Jordan 11 and Air Max ’97. According to CNN, United States residents go wild over these shoes. Shoe collectors are sometimes willing to pay up to $2,000 for a pair of legitimate ones. If you’re looking for your next pair, however, you might want to double-check before you buy. Customs and Border Protection said consumers are likely to see fake Nikes online. ⤕Climate Change: Chevron, Exxon, Shell, others cause one-third world carbon emission ⤕Private account used in running Imo Transport Company ― Chairman “Counterfeit brand-name shoes [such as fake Nike] is a multi-million dollar criminal industry,” LaFonda Sutton-Burke, CBP port director of the Los Angeles/Long Beach Seaport, said in a news release, according to CNN report. “The trafficking of these items [such as fake Nike] is extremely lucrative and becomes more profitable in markets involving successful and popular products.” The trade-in illegitimate goods is associated with smuggling and other criminal activities, and often funds criminal enterprises, Customs and Border Patrol said. Vanguard News Nigeria. A new world record for a pair of sneakers was set at auction on Tuesday when an avid collector splashed out $437,500 on Nike's 1972 "Moon Shoe," Sotheby's said. July 24, 2019 In "News" US presidential candidate Donald Trump has pledged to bring long lost American manufacturing jobs back from China. But he may be too late -- even for products that bear his family name. October 6, 2016 In "News" ...as manufacturers, other stakeholders react The increasing menace of dumping of products from Asian countries, especially China, into the Nigerian market is seriously undermining the competitiveness of the nation’s already distressed manufacturing sector. April 2, 2012 In "Finance"